string- sequence of characters. it can be quoted in single, double or triple quotes.
a string can't be concatenated with an integer.
operator * is used to repeat string a number of times. eg: hello*5 will print hello 5 times 
Relational operators - ==,<,>,<=,>=,!
they are used for comparing expressions and yield results in the form of true or false
arithmetic operators have higher precedence then relational operators 
when relational operators are applied to string then it is operated from left to right, character to character using ASCII codes where  codes of 'A-Z' are (65,90), for 'a-z' are (97,122) and for (0,,9) are (48,57)
logical operators:- not, and, or 
not is a unary operator i.e. it requires ony one operand. not True is false and not false is true.
and gives true only when both operands are true  gives false otherwise.
or gives false when both opernds are false gives true otherwise.
logical operators have precedency as not,and then or
also arithmetic operators, then relational and then logical operators are solved as per precedency.
short ut evaluation of boolean expressions:- expression invloving and gets its second sub expression evaluated only when the first gives true as a result. similary an expression involving or gets its second sub expression evaluated ony ehrn the first one gives false as a result.
